Python Foundations Project: Austo¶

Marks: 60

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

In the 21st century, cars are an important mode of transportation that provides us the opportunity for personal control and autonomy. In day-to-day life, people use cars for commuting to work, shopping, visiting family and friends, etc. Research shows that more than 76% of people prevent themselves from traveling somewhere if they don't have a car. Most people tend to buy different types of cars based on their day-to-day necessities and preferences. So, it is essential for automobile companies to analyze the preference of their customers before launching a car model into the market. Austo, a UK-based automobile company aspires to grow its business into the US market after successfully establishing its footprints in the European market.

In order to be familiar with the types of cars preferred by the customers and factors influencing the car purchase behavior in the US market, Austo has contracted a consulting firm. Based on various market surveys, the consulting firm has created a dataset of 3 major types of cars that are extensively used across the US market. They have collected various details of the car owners which can be analyzed to understand the automobile market of the US.

Objective¶

Austo's management team wants to understand the demand of the buyers and trends in the US market. They want to build customer profiles based on the analysis to identify new purchase opportunities so that they can manipulate the business strategy and production to meet certain demand levels. Further, the analysis will be a good way for management to understand the dynamics of a new market. Suppose you are a Data Scientist working at the consulting firm that has been contracted by Austo. You are given the task to create buyer's profiles for different types of cars with the available data as well as a set of recommendations for Austo. Perform the data analysis to generate useful insights that will help the automobile company to grow its business.

Data Description¶

austo_automobile.csv: The dataset contains buyer's data corresponding to different types of products(cars).

Data Dictionary¶

  • Age: Age of the customer
  • Gender: Gender of the customer
  • Profession: Indicates whether the customer is a salaried or business person
  • Marital_status: Marital status of the customer
  • Education: Refers to the highest level of education completed by the customer
  • No_of_dependents: Number of dependents(partner/children/spouse) of the customer
  • Personal_loan: Indicates whether the customer availed a personal loan or not
  • House_loan: Indicates whether the customer availed house loan or not
  • Partner_working: Indicates whether the customer's partner is working or not
  • Salary: Annual Salary of the customer
  • Partner_salary: Annual Salary of the customer's partner
  • Total_salary: Annual household income (Salary + Partner_salary) of the customer's family
  • Price: Price of the car
  • Make: Car type (Hatchback/Sedan/SUV)

Observations on Partner Salary¶
  • The data shows almost 50% of partners as having 0 USD income, but this correstponds to the 713 buyers whose partner does not work (inlcuding the 138 buyers who are single). This is helpful to know in of itself, half of buyers are single-income homes.
  • Of the partners that do work, 75% of have annual salary between 22k and 40k USD, with 59 outlier partners making 60k - 80k USD. Nearly all non-outlier partners would all be in the lowest quartile if they themselves were the buyers in the data set.
  • Americans largely do not have access to state provided child, disabled, or eldercare; and given that most of these families have 2+ depenedents - there is a lot of unpaid labor in this data set. The lower partner incomes also could represent part time work, or the wage gap after pausing career for early child care.

Multivariate Analysis¶

Question 9: Perform a multivariate analysis to explore relationships between the important variables in the dataset. (It is a good idea to explore relations between numerical variables as well as relations between numerical and categorical variables) [15 marks]¶

Observations on numeric correlations¶
  • The Price and Age in this dataset are highly correlated at 0.79. Older buyers are buying more expensive cars.
  • The Price and Salary/TotalSalary correlations are positive, but lower at 0.39 and 0.35 respectively. This implies the pattern of buying a car might depend less on cost/salary and more on other factors.
  • The Total Salary being more highly correlated to Partner Salary than to Salary makes sense; as the presence of a second income in half the data set would cause the $0 partner salaries to have a large effect on the total.
  • The Age being more highly correlated to Salary than the Total Salary also makes sense; as the primary earners can expect to see an increase in salary as they age. Partner salaries, however, would not similarly correlate with age as many stay 0 USD through their lifetime or grow less rapidly than the primary earners - as seen with the 0.15 correlation value.

Observations on buying behavior¶
  • Buying behavior is very tied to Age, followed secondly by number of dependents. Complete buyer profiles available in conclusions.
  • Buying behavior is largely independent of Salary data, Marital Status, Personal Loans, House Loans, Working Partners, Education.
  • No Pattern was found to explain pricing considerations; there appears to be no data driven reason why a buyer would buy (as an example) the 32k Hatchback over the 18k Hatchback.

This gives us a starting position for several conversations.

Age

  • Buyers who spend more money than they make in a year tend to be 30-50 years old and buying Sedans and SUVs
  • Older buyers are spending more money and they make more money. *Older buyers are more likely to have partners with high salaries.
  • The dataset has a gap - there are no very few young 30's buyers with 3+ dependents. Their older and younger conterparts do.

No of Dependents

  • No correlation between number of dependents and spending habit (difference)
  • Sedans are only purchased by families with 1-2 dependents
  • No real correlation between number of dependents and salary data

Salary Data

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 12: Write the conclusions and business recommendations derived from the analysis. (6 marks)¶

Conclusions¶

As Austo considers enter the US car market, they should aim to choose or adapt a current product from their fleet that is a family-friendly vehicle that can be marketed to one of the below profiles.

Buyer Profiles¶

There are four major buyer profiles in this dataset. These profiles are driven most by the age of the buyer and the number of dependents they are supporting with the vehicle. Since gender, salary, usage of loans, marital status, and education are not essential factors to their buying decisions these profiles focus on age and dependents.

Hatchback Buyer Profile (18k - 33k)

These buyers are aged 22-32 and generally have 2+ dependents. They are likely buying a vehicle that is safe, easy to install car seats, or has otherwise has utility for their larger, younger families.

Sedan Buyer Profile (36k- 55k)

These buyers are aged 35-45 and have 1-2 dependents. These dependents are likely older children or the buyers elderly relatives and can handle a sleeker, likely more fuel efficient vehicle.

SUV, Type 1 Buyer Profile (49k-70k)

These buyers are aged 35-45, have 3 or more dependents. (Incidentally, they also make less than their peers in their profession, and do not have house loans) While most buyers in this age demographic have 1-2 dependents, and thus belong to the Sedan Buyer Profile, this is a small but mighty buying group. Their buying decision for the move expensive SUV is likely due to necessary space to fit the larger, older family.

SUV, Type 2 Buyer Profile (49k-70k)

These buyers are aged 45-60 and have 2+ dependents. More collaboration with data team required to explain why SUVs for this demographic.

Recommendations for further data exploration and analysis¶

Considering pricing has to be the next greatest hurdle. This dataset did not propose a reason why buyers would participate in the bottom vs the top of the price range for their vehicle type. Is this something about the car - brand, safety features, electric vs gasoline? Or something about the demographic not included in the data set - city, credit score?

Expand data to include consideration of target markets; given the current demographics - look for mid size cities with large suburb and less rural surrondings. This requires its own analysis, but this particual american "consultant" suggests mid-size cities of North Carolina, Texas, and Arizona.

Expand data to include manufactorers, so analysis can be run on competitors. Is Austo - the company we are considering - more like BMW (high budget, over quarter million sales in USA) or Fiat (low budget, less than 10k sales in USA)? Do these profiles hold up when considering competitor data? Does it make more sense to enter a city with or without competitor dealerships?

Current data is only considering middle class, educated americans with dependents, mostly early career. Is this the demographic of Austo buyers in their European markets? If not - consider matching demographics closer to buyers in European markets. The US market has many buyers outside the rather narrow scope of this data set.

The scope of this project only considers buyer profiles - but next steps in considering the buyer's decision making could also include:

  • Maintanence costs research: Are the parts and labor costs for these european cars accessible, affordable for the targeted buyers? If not, will dealerships have a loaner program (like some of their competitors?).
  • Dealership or Showroom: Are potential buyers traveling to a big city dealership and driving away with their car today, or will the cars be presented ona showroom floor and ordered?
  • In house financing: since half the buyers are using personal loans, does Austro have the capacity to offer competitive financing as part of their sales deal?
